The pattern for configuration in .Net Core is to resolve `IOptions<MyConfigurationClass>` through dependency injection.  aws-sdk should support this pattern, in addition to `AWSOptions`.

## Expected Behavior
```csharp
services.Configure<ClientConfig>(SomeConfiguration);    //I may resolve IOptions<ClientConfig> in other, more exotic ways than through an IConfiguration
services.AddAWSService<IAmazonS3>();    //I haven't provided AWSOptions, nor have I called AddDefaultAWSOptions to configure a default

...

class DoS3Things
{
  public DoS3Things(IAmazonS3 s3)
  {
    //S3 is configured based on IOptions<ClientConfig>
  }
}
```

## Current Behavior
```csharp
services.AddDefaultAWSOptions(Configuration.GetAWSOptions());  //This assumes many things about my configuration files and dependency injection requirements
services.AddAWSService<IAmazonS3>();

...

class DoS3Things
{
  public DoS3Things(IAmazonS3 s3)
  {
    //S3 is configured based on AWSOptions which loaded its configuration from IConfiguration
  }
}
```

## Context
Our projects resolve configuration both through the simple IConfiguration functionality, as well as more complex methods like searching IConfiguration for top-level elements that match the namespace and type of the requested IOptions.  To resolve configuration for AWS using our existing functionality, we'd like aws-sdk to conform to the .Net Core configuration pattern of resolving IOptions<MyConfigurationClass> through DI.  The current GetAWSOptions functionality supports many use cases, but also makes assumptions about how Configuration is arranged and implemented locally.

## Expected Behaviour
The retrieval of temporary security credentials from instance metadata should not cause performance degradation when using the SDK with multiple Tasks.

## Current Behaviour
The retrieval of temporary security credentials performs well when requests to AWS are made consecutively.  However, processing is significantly delayed when the refreshing of temporary security credentials is required whilst concurrent requests are performed.

## Steps to Reproduce (for bugs)
Run the following console application using an EC2 instance with an instance profile.  Amazon Linux, Ubuntu and Windows all exhibit the same behaviour.
```c#
using Amazon.SimpleNotificationService;
using Amazon.SimpleNotificationService.Model;
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Diagnostics;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class Program
{
    private static AmazonSimpleNotificationServiceClient client;

    public static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        client = new AmazonSimpleNotificationServiceClient();

        //PerformTest1().Wait();  // Uncomment this line to observe normal behaviour
        PerformTest2().Wait();
    }

    private static async Task PerformTest1()
    {
        var stopwatch = new Stopwatch();

        stopwatch.Start();

        await PublishMessage();

        stopwatch.Stop();

        Console.WriteLine($"Test 1 Elapsed time: {stopwatch.Elapsed.TotalSeconds} seconds");
    }

    private static async Task PerformTest2()
    {
        var stopwatch = new Stopwatch();
        var tasks = new List<Task<PublishResponse>>();

        stopwatch.Start();

        for (int counter = 0; counter < 20; counter++)
        {
            tasks.Add(Task.Run(async () => await PublishMessage()));
        }

        await Task.WhenAll(tasks);

        stopwatch.Stop();

        Console.WriteLine($"Test 2 Elapsed time: {stopwatch.Elapsed.TotalSeconds} seconds");
    }

    private static async Task<PublishResponse> PublishMessage() => await client.PublishAsync("arn:aws:sns:ap-southeast-2:111111111111:topic", "yo");
}
```
The `PerformTest1` method publishes a single message to an SNS topic.  The `PerformTest2` method publishes 20 messages to the SNS topic using Tasks.

Below is the execution time of the `PerformTest2` method when preceded by the `PerformTest1` method (to avoid rival fetching of security credentials):

> C:\ConsoleApp1>dotnet run
Test 1 Elapsed time: 0.2750664 seconds
Test 2 Elapsed time: **0.0763104 seconds**


Below is the execution time of the `PerformTest2` method without first running `PerformTest1`:

> C:\ConsoleApp1>dotnet run
Test 2 Elapsed time: **18.2262467 seconds**

## Context
We have various applications that do not make AWS calls for extended periods of time (e.g. an hour).  These applications are also required to handle sporadic load.  The retrieval of temporary credentials when performing concurrent processing can cause delays of over a minute compared to the normal processing time of around 200ms.

dotTrace has highlighted `Amazon.Runtime.InstanceProfileAWSCredentials.GenerateNewCredentials` as a major performance bottleneck for us.

