I've had the same issue.  The MD5 is use for verifying uploads and in the download area.  Interestingly if you're performing a multi-part upload the MD5 is not checked (see AmazonS3Client.Extensions.cs in the CompareHashes(string etag, byte[] hash) function)

I looked and the fault occurs when a the Init() in the HashingWrapper class is invoked by calling
HashAlgorithm.Create(algorithmName) where algorithmName is a non compliant algorithm.  The acceptable inputs are listed here http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/wet69s13%28v=vs.90%29.aspx.  Compliant algorithms are generally not managed and not MD5.  There's some interesting code to list out the compliant ones here http://blogs.msdn.com/b/icumove/archive/2009/01/31/working-with-fips-in-net-c.aspx?Redirected=true

Solution:
Since the MD5 check is an "added" feature and not critical (see the multi-part comments) then we need to detect FIPS and process accordingly.  Note:  I'm using this with the AmazonS3EncryptionClient using asymmetric encryption and signing of the data object, therefore the MD5 hash is redundant. I'm not sure of the MD5s function, see discussion below)

I haven't found a good .Net reference to detect FIPS (like BCryptGetFipsAlgorithmMode function) without calling and catching the error.  When / if that is located the try/catch statements will be changed to if/else.  Until then I performed  the following modifications:

1) Created FipsUtility.cs in Amazon.Util folder and added.  It uses the try/catch instead of an unsafe call to BCryptGetFipsAlgorithmMode.  This uses processes similar to the internal Utils.FipsAlgorithmPolicy.

```
using System.Security;
using System.Security.Permissions;
using Microsoft.Win32;
namespace AWSSDK.Amazon.Util
{
    public static class FipsUtility
    {
        static int fipsAlgorithmPolicy = -1;
        // Federal Information Processing Standards Publications
        // at http://www.itl.nist.gov/fipspubs/geninfo.htm
        public static bool RequiresFipsCompliance
        { 

            get
            {
                // Check once
                if (fipsAlgorithmPolicy == -1)
                { 
                       try
                        {
                            System.Security.Cryptography.HashAlgorithm.Create("MD5");
                            fipsAlgorithmPolicy = 0;
                        }
                        catch (System.Reflection.TargetInvocationException)
                        {
                            fipsAlgorithmPolicy = 1;
                        }   
                } 
                return fipsAlgorithmPolicy == 1;
            } 
        }
    }
}
```

 2) In HashStream.cs added a FIPS compliant WrapperClass to the file
    Note:  This will be unable to compare to the AWS hash and therefore implementation of SHA1 is simply to provide a simple wrapper.  A good modification for S3 might be to return an SHA256 or higher hash.

```
public class HashingWrapperGeneric : HashingWrapper
{
    //Implement an unmanaged algorythm see http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/wet69s13%28v=vs.90%29.aspx
    private static string genericAlgorithmName = "SHA1";

    public HashingWrapperGeneric()
        : base(genericAlgorithmName)
    { }
}
```

  3) In HashStream.cs  I added GenericHashStream to provide a FIPS compliant alternative to MD5Stream

```
public class GenericHashStream : HashStream<HashingWrapperGeneric>
{
    #region Constructors

    public GenericHashStream(Stream baseStream, byte[] expectedHash, long expectedLength)
        : base(baseStream, expectedHash, expectedLength) { }

    #endregion
}
```

