Amazon S3 MD5 Discussion:
  I'm trying to identify the threat using the etag with the object externally to AWS mitigates.  Internally it makes perfect sense to track the integrity of objects and having a reference.  Externally by itself the etag is a good resource to inventory the S3 containers unencrypted content without downloading all of the content.  But in this scenario comparing the downloaded object to the etag is either redundant to the transport mechanism or ineffective to MITM attacks since the etag and object use the same transport.  This is the same flaw most sites publishing data and hashes have.  If I can alter the data on the site, or in transit, I can alter the hash too.  A better solution would be signed SHA256 hashes.

